Pod logs
   ↓
Grafana Alloy (collects logs)
   ↓
Loki (stores + indexes logs)
   ↓
Grafana (searches + displays logs)

The big practical win for you specifically: if a pod crashes and gets replaced (which happens constantly with Karpenter scaling nodes 
up/down, or during deployments), kubectl logs on the old pod is gone. But in Loki, those logs are still there because Alloy already 
shipped them off the node before the pod died.

+---------------+------------------------------------------------------------------+-------------------------------------------------+
| Component     | Deployment type                                                  | Why                                             |
+---------------+------------------------------------------------------------------+-------------------------------------------------+
| Alloy         | DaemonSet                                                        | Needs local access to log files per node        |
+---------------+------------------------------------------------------------------+-------------------------------------------------+
| Node Exporter | DaemonSet                                                        | Needs local access to node OS metrics           |
+---------------+------------------------------------------------------------------+-------------------------------------------------+
| Prometheus    | Deployment/StatefulSet (or fully managed if using Grafana Cloud) | Central scraper; doesn't need per-node presence |
+---------------+------------------------------------------------------------------+-------------------------------------------------+
| Loki          | Deployment/StatefulSet (or fully managed if using Grafana Cloud) | Central log store; receives pushed data         |
+---------------+------------------------------------------------------------------+-------------------------------------------------+
| Grafana       | Deployment                                                       | Central UI/query layer                          |
+---------------+------------------------------------------------------------------+-------------------------------------------------+


